[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Such examples may arouse suspicions of being generated by a different mechanism, or appear inconsistent with the remainder of that set of data.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection finds application in many domains including cybersecurity, medicine, machine vision, statistics, neuroscience, law enforcement and financial fraud to name only a few.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Anomalies were initially searched for clear rejection or omission from the data to aid statistical analysis, for example to compute the mean or standard deviation.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] They were also removed to better predictions from models such as linear regression, and more recently their removal aids the performance of machine learning algorithms.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] However, in many applications anomalies themselves are of interest and are the observations most desirous in the entire data set, which need to be identified and separated from noise or irrelevant outliers.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Many attempts have been made in the statistical and computer science communities to define an anomaly.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] The concept of intrusion detection, a critical component of anomaly detection, has evolved significantly over time.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Initially, it was a manual process where system administrators would monitor for unusual activities, such as a vacationing user's account being accessed or unexpected printer activity.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] This approach was not scalable and was soon superseded by the analysis of audit logs and system logs for signs of malicious behavior.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] By the late 1970s and early 1980s, the analysis of these logs was primarily used retrospectively to investigate incidents, as the volume of data made it impractical for real-time monitoring.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] The affordability of digital storage eventually led to audit logs being analyzed online, with specialized programs being developed to sift through the data.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] These programs, however, were typically run during off-peak hours due to their computational intensity.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] The 1990s brought the advent of real-time intrusion detection systems capable of analyzing audit data as it was generated, allowing for immediate detection of and response to attacks.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] This marked a significant shift towards proactive intrusion detection.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] As the field has continued to develop, the focus has shifted to creating solutions that can be efficiently implemented across large and complex network environments, adapting to the ever-growing variety of security threats and the dynamic nature of modern computing infrastructures.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is applicable in a very large number and variety of domains, and is an important subarea of unsupervised machine learning.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] As such it has applications in cyber-security, intrusion detection, fraud detection, fault detection, system health monitoring, event detection in sensor networks, detecting ecosystem disturbances, defect detection in images using machine vision, medical diagnosis and law enforcement.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection was proposed for intrusion detection systems (IDS) by Dorothy Denning in 1986.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection for IDS is normally accomplished with thresholds and statistics, but can also be done with soft computing, and inductive learning.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Types of features proposed by 1999 included profiles of users, workstations, networks, remote hosts, groups of users, and programs based on frequencies, means, variances, covariances, and standard deviations.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] The counterpart of anomaly detection in intrusion detection is misuse detection.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is vital in fintech for fraud prevention.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Preprocessing data to remove anomalies can be an important step in data analysis, and is done for a number of reasons.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Statistics such as the mean and standard deviation are more accurate after the removal of anomalies, and the visualisation of data can also be improved.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] In supervised learning, removing the anomalous data from the dataset often results in a statistically significant increase in accuracy.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection has become increasingly vital in video surveillance to enhance security and safety.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] With the advent of deep learning technologies, methods using Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Simple Recurrent Units (SRUs) have shown significant promise in identifying unusual activities or behaviors in video data.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] These models can process and analyze extensive video feeds in real-time, recognizing patterns that deviate from the norm, which may indicate potential security threats or safety violations.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] An important aspect for video surveillance is the development of scalable real-time frameworks.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Such pipelines are required for processing multiple video streams with low computational resources.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] In IT infrastructure management, anomaly detection is crucial for ensuring the smooth operation and reliability of services.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] These are complex systems, composed of many interactive elements and large data quantities, requiring methods to process and reduce this data into a human and machine interpretable format.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Techniques like the IT Infrastructure Library (ITIL) and monitoring frameworks are employed to track and manage system performance and user experience.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Detected anomalies can help identify and pre-empt potential performance degradations or system failures, thus maintaining productivity and business process effectiveness.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is critical for the security and efficiency of Internet of Things (IoT) systems.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] It helps in identifying system failures and security breaches in complex networks of IoT devices.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] The methods must manage real-time data, diverse device types, and scale effectively.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Garg et al. have introduced a multi-stage anomaly detection framework that improves upon traditional methods by incorporating spatial clustering, density-based clustering, and locality-sensitive hashing.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] This tailored approach is designed to better handle the vast and varied nature of IoT data, thereby enhancing security and operational reliability in smart infrastructure and industrial IoT systems.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is crucial in the petroleum industry for monitoring critical machinery.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] A 2015 paper proposed a novel segmentation algorithm using support vector machines to analyze sensor data for real-time anomaly detection.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] In the oil and gas sector, anomaly detection is not just crucial for maintenance and safety, but also for environmental protection.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Aljameel et al. propose an advanced machine learning-based model for detecting minor leaks in oil and gas pipelines, a task traditional methods may miss.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Many anomaly detection techniques have been proposed in literature.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] The performance of methods usually depend on the data sets.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] For example, some may be suited to detecting local outliers, while others global, and methods have little systematic advantages over another when compared across many data sets.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Almost all algorithms also require the setting of non-intuitive parameters critical for performance, and usually unknown before application.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] The size of bins are key to the effectiveness of this technique but must be determined by the implementer.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] A more sophisticated technique uses kernel functions to approximate the distribution of the normal data.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Instances in low probability areas of the distribution are then considered anomalies.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Quantum machine learning approaches have been investigated for anomaly detection on near-term quantum hardware.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Quantum support vector machines (QSVMs) using quantum kernel methods, such as the ZZFeatureMap, have been applied to classification of normal versus anomalous instances by leveraging high-dimensional quantum feature spaces.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Histogram-based Outlier Score (HBOS) uses value histograms and assumes feature independence for fast predictions.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Dynamic networks, such as those representing financial systems, social media interactions, and transportation infrastructure, are subject to constant change, making anomaly detection within them a complex task.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Unlike static graphs, dynamic networks reflect evolving relationships and states, requiring adaptive techniques for anomaly detection.
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] Many of the methods discussed above only yield an anomaly score prediction, which often can be explained to users as the point being in a region of low data density (or relatively low density compared to the neighbor's densities).
[src:falco-runtime/anomaly-detection] In explainable artificial intelligence, the users demand methods with higher explainability.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:falco-runtime/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] The **Berkeley Packet Filter** (**BPF**; also **BSD Packet Filter**, **classic BPF** or **cBPF**) is a network tap mechanism and packet filter which permits computer network packets to be captured and filtered at the operating system level.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] It provides a raw interface to data link layers, permitting raw link-layer packets to be sent and received, and allows a userspace process to supply a filter program that specifies which packets it wants to receive.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] For example, a tcpdump process may want to receive only packets that initiate a TCP connection.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] BPF returns only packets that pass the filter that the process supplies.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] This avoids copying unwanted packets from the operating system kernel to the process, greatly improving performance.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] The filter program is in the form of instructions for a virtual machine, which are interpreted, or compiled into machine code by a just-in-time (JIT) mechanism and executed, in the kernel.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is used by programs that need to, among other things, analyze network traffic.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] If the driver for the network interface supports promiscuous mode, it allows the interface to be put into that mode so that all packets on the network can be received, even those destined to other hosts.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] The BPF filtering mechanism is available on most Unix-like operating systems.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is sometimes used to refer to just the filtering mechanism, rather than to the entire interface.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Some systems, such as Linux and Tru64 UNIX, provide a raw interface to the data link layer other than the BPF raw interface but use the BPF filtering mechanisms for that raw interface.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] The Linux kernel provides an extended version of the BPF filtering mechanism, called eBPF, which uses a JIT mechanism, and which is used for packet filtering, as well as for other purposes in the kernel. eBPF is also available for Microsoft Windows.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] The original paper was written by Steven McCanne and Van Jacobson in 1992 while at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] BPF provides pseudo-devices that can be bound to a network interface; reads from the device will read buffers full of packets received on the network interface, and writes to the device will inject packets on the network interface.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] While one copy remains in the receipt path for user processes, this preserves the independence of different BPF device consumers, as well as allowing the packing of headers into the BPF buffer rather than copying complete packet data.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] BPF's filtering capabilities are implemented as an interpreter for a machine language for the BPF virtual machine, a 32-bit machine with fixed-length instructions, one accumulator, and one index register.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Programs in that language can fetch data from the packet, perform arithmetic operations on data from the packet, and compare the results against constants or against data in the packet or test bits in the results, accepting or rejecting the packet based on the results of those tests.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is often extended by "overloading" the load (ld) and store (str) instructions.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Traditional Unix-like BPF implementations can be used in userspace, despite being written for kernel-space.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] This is accomplished using preprocessor conditions.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Since version 3.18, the Linux kernel includes an extended BPF virtual machine with ten 64-bit registers, termed eBPF.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] It can be used for non-networking purposes, such as for attaching eBPF programs to various tracepoints.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Since kernel version 3.19, eBPF filters can be attached to sockets, and, since kernel version 4.1, to traffic control classifiers for the ingress and egress networking data path.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] The original and obsolete version has been retroactively renamed to *classic BPF* (*cBPF*).
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Nowadays, the Linux kernel runs eBPF only and loaded cBPF bytecode is transparently translated into an eBPF representation in the kernel before program execution.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] All bytecode is verified before running to prevent denial-of-service attacks.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Until Linux 5.3, the verifier prohibited the use of loops, to prevent potentially unbounded execution times; loops with bounded execution time are now permitted in more recent kernels.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Some projects use BPF instruction sets or execution techniques different from the originals.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Some platforms, including FreeBSD, NetBSD, and WinPcap, use a just-in-time compiler (JIT) to convert BPF instructions into native code in order to improve performance.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Linux includes a BPF JIT compiler which is disabled by default.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Kernel-mode interpreters for that same virtual machine language are used in raw data link layer mechanisms in other operating systems, such as Tru64 Unix, and for socket filters in the Linux kernel and in the WinPcap and Npcap packet capture mechanism.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] That interpreter can also be used when reading a file containing packets captured using pcap.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Another user-mode interpreter is *uBPF*, which supports JIT and eBPF (without cBPF).
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Its code has been reused to provide eBPF support in non-Linux systems.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Microsoft's *eBPF on Windows* builds on uBPF and the PREVAIL formal verifier.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] *rBPF*, a Rust rewrite of uBPF, is used by the Solana blockchain platform as the execution engine.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Classic BPF is generally emitted by a program from some very high-level textual rule describing the pattern to match.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] One such representation is found in libpcap.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Classic BPF and eBPF can also be written either directly as machine code, or using an assembly language for a textual representation.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Notable assemblers include Linux kernel's `bpf_asm` tool (cBPF), `bpfc` (cBPF), and the `ubpf` assembler (eBPF).
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] The `bpftool` command can also act as a disassembler for both flavors of BPF.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] The assembly languages are not necessarily compatible with each other.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] eBPF bytecode has recently become a target of higher-level languages.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] LLVM added eBPF support in 2014, and GCC followed in 2019.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Both toolkits allow compiling C and other supported languages to eBPF.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] A subset of P4 can also be compiled into eBPF using BCC, an LLVM-based compiler kit.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] The Spectre attack could leverage the Linux kernel's eBPF interpreter or JIT compiler to extract data from other kernel processes.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] A JIT hardening feature in the kernel mitigates this vulnerability.
[src:falco-runtime/extended-berkeley-packet-filter] Chinese computer security group Pangu Lab said the NSA used BPF to conceal network communications as part of a complex Linux backdoor.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] An **intrusion detection system** (**IDS**) is a device or software application that monitors a network or systems for malicious activity or policy violations.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Any intrusion activity or violation is typically either reported to an administrator or collected centrally using a security information and event management (SIEM) system.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] A SIEM system combines outputs from multiple sources and uses alarm filtering techniques to distinguish malicious activity from false alarms.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] IDS types range in scope from single computers to large networks.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The most common classifications are **network intrusion detection systems** (**NIDS**) and **host-based intrusion detection systems** (**HIDS**).
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] A system that monitors important operating system files is an example of an HIDS, while a system that analyzes incoming network traffic is an example of an NIDS.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] It is also possible to classify IDS by detection approach.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The most well-known variants are signature-based detection (recognizing bad patterns, such as exploitation attempts) and anomaly-based detection (detecting deviations from a model of "good" traffic, which often relies on machine learning).
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Another common variant is reputation-based detection (recognizing the potential threat according to the reputation scores).
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Some IDS products have the ability to respond to detected intrusions.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Systems with response capabilities are typically referred to as an **intrusion prevention system** (**IPS**).
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection systems can also serve specific purposes by augmenting them with custom tools, such as using a honeypot to attract and characterize malicious traffic.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Although they both relate to network security, an IDS differs from a firewall in that a conventional network firewall (distinct from a next-generation firewall) uses a static set of rules to permit or deny network connections.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] It implicitly prevents intrusions, assuming an appropriate set of rules have been defined.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Essentially, firewalls limit access between networks to prevent intrusion and do not signal an attack from inside the network.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS describes a suspected intrusion once it has taken place and signals an alarm.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS also watches for attacks that originate from within a system.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] This is traditionally achieved by examining network communications, identifying heuristics and patterns (often known as signatures) of common computer attacks, and taking action to alert operators.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] A system that terminates connections is called an intrusion prevention system, and performs access control like an application layer firewall.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] IDS can be classified by where detection takes place (network or host) or the detection method that is employed (signature or anomaly-based).
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Network intrusion detection systems (NIDS) are placed at a strategic point or points within the network to monitor traffic to and from all devices on the network.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] It performs an analysis of passing traffic on the entire subnet, and matches the traffic that is passed on the subnets to the library of known attacks.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Once an attack is identified, or abnormal behavior is sensed, the alert can be sent to the administrator.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS function to safeguard every device and the entire network from unauthorized access.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] An example of an NIDS would be installing it on the subnet where firewalls are located in order to see if someone is trying to break into the firewall.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Ideally one would scan all inbound and outbound traffic, however doing so might create a bottleneck that would impair the overall speed of the network.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] OPNET and NetSim are commonly used tools for simulating network intrusion detection systems.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] NID Systems are also capable of comparing signatures for similar packets to link and drop harmful detected packets which have a signature matching the records in the NIDS.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] When we classify the design of the NIDS according to the system interactivity property, there are two types: on-line and off-line NIDS, often referred to as inline and tap mode, respectively.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] On-line NIDS deals with the network in real time.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] It analyses the Ethernet packets and applies some rules, to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Off-line NIDS deals with stored data and passes it through some processes to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS can be also combined with other technologies to increase detection and prediction rates.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Artificial Neural Network (ANN) based IDS are capable of analyzing huge volumes of data due to the hidden layers and non-linear modeling, however this process requires time due its complex structure.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] This allows IDS to more efficiently recognize intrusion patterns.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Neural networks assist IDS in predicting attacks by learning from mistakes; ANN based IDS help develop an early warning system, based on two layers.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The first layer accepts single values, while the second layer takes the first's layers output as input; the cycle repeats and allows the system to automatically recognize new unforeseen patterns in the network.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] This system can average 99.9% detection and classification rate, based on research results of 24 network attacks, divided in four categories: DOS, Probe, Remote-to-Local, and user-to-root.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Host intrusion detection systems (HIDS) run on individual hosts or devices on the network.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS monitors the inbound and outbound packets from the device only and will alert the user or administrator if suspicious activity is detected.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] It takes a snapshot of existing system files and matches it to the previous snapshot.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] If the critical system files were modified or deleted, an alert is sent to the administrator to investigate.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] An example of HIDS usage can be seen on mission critical machines, which are not expected to change their configurations.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Signature-based IDS is the detection of attacks by looking for specific patterns, such as byte sequences in network traffic, or known malicious instruction sequences used by malware.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] This terminology originates from anti-virus software, which refers to these detected patterns as signatures.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Although signature-based IDS can easily detect known attacks, it is difficult to detect new attacks, for which no pattern is available.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] In signature-based IDS, the signatures are released by a vendor for all its products.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] On-time updating of the IDS with the signature is a key aspect.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Anomaly-based intrusion detection systems were primarily introduced to detect unknown attacks, in part due to the rapid development of malware.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The basic approach is to use machine learning to create a model of trustworthy activity, and then compare new behavior against this model.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Since these models can be trained according to the applications and hardware configurations, machine learning based method has a better generalized property in comparison to traditional signature-based IDS.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Although this approach enables the detection of previously unknown attacks, it may suffer from false positives: previously unknown legitimate activity may also be classified as malicious.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Most of the existing IDSs suffer from the time-consuming during detection process that degrades the performance of IDSs.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Efficient feature selection algorithm makes the classification process used in detection more reliable.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Recent research has also explored deep learning approaches for anomaly-based intrusion detection, as these methods can learn complex traffic patterns and help identify previously unseen attacks more effectively.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] New types of what could be called anomaly-based intrusion detection systems are being viewed by Gartner as User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA) (an evolution of the user behavior analytics category) and network traffic analysis (NTA).
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] In particular, NTA deals with malicious insiders as well as targeted external attacks that have compromised a user machine or account.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Gartner has noted that some organizations have opted for NTA over more traditional IDS.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Some systems may attempt to stop an intrusion attempt but this is neither required nor expected of a monitoring system.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDPS) are primarily focused on identifying possible incidents, logging information about them, and reporting attempts.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] In addition, organizations use IDPS for other purposes, such as identifying problems with security policies, documenting existing threats and deterring individuals from violating security policies.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS have become a necessary addition to the security infrastructure of nearly every organization.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS typically record information related to observed events, notify security administrators of important observed events and produce reports.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Many IDPS can also respond to a detected threat by attempting to prevent it from succeeding.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] They use several response techniques, which involve the IDPS stopping the attack itself, changing the security environment (e.g. reconfiguring a firewall) or changing the attack's content.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion prevention systems are considered extensions of intrusion detection systems because they both monitor network traffic and/or system activities for malicious activity.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The main differences are, unlike intrusion detection systems, intrusion prevention systems are placed in-line and are able to actively prevent or block intrusions that are detected.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] IPS can take such actions as sending an alarm, dropping detected malicious packets, resetting a connection or blocking traffic from the offending IP address.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] An IPS also can correct cyclic redundancy check (CRC) errors, defragment packet streams, mitigate TCP sequencing issues, and clean up unwanted transport and network layer options.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] **Wireless intrusion prevention system (WIPS)**: monitor a wireless network for suspicious traffic by analyzing wireless networking protocols.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] **Network behavior analysis (NBA)**: examines network traffic to identify threats that generate unusual traffic flows, such as distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks, certain forms of malware and policy violations.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] **Host-based intrusion prevention system (HIPS)**: an installed software package which monitors a single host for suspicious activity by analyzing events occurring within that host.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The majority of intrusion prevention systems utilize one of three detection methods: signature-based, statistical anomaly-based, and stateful protocol analysis.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] **Statistical anomaly-based detection**: An IDS which is anomaly-based will monitor network traffic and compare it against an established baseline.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The baseline will identify what is "normal" for that network – what sort of bandwidth is generally used and what protocols are used.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] It may however, raise a False Positive alarm for legitimate use of bandwidth if the baselines are not intelligently configured.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Ensemble models that use Matthews correlation co-efficient to identify unauthorized network traffic have obtained 99.73% accuracy.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] **Stateful protocol analysis detection**: This method identifies deviations of protocol states by comparing observed events with "pre-determined profiles of generally accepted definitions of benign activity".
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] While it is capable of knowing and tracing the protocol states, it requires significant resources.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The correct placement of intrusion detection systems is critical and varies depending on the network.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The most common placement is behind the firewall, on the edge of a network.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] This practice provides the IDS with high visibility of traffic entering your network and will not receive any traffic between users on the network.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The edge of the network is the point in which a network connects to the extranet.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] If an IDS is placed beyond a network's firewall, its main purpose would be to defend against noise from the internet but, more importantly, defend against common attacks, such as port scans and network mapper.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS in this position would monitor layers 4 through 7 of the OSI model and would be signature-based.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] This is a very useful practice, because rather than showing actual breaches into the network that made it through the firewall, attempted breaches will be shown which reduces the amount of false positives.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The IDS in this position also assists in decreasing the amount of time it takes to discover successful attacks against a network.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Sometimes an IDS with more advanced features will be integrated with a firewall in order to be able to intercept sophisticated attacks entering the network.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Examples of advanced features would include multiple security contexts in the routing level and bridging mode.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] All of this in turn potentially reduces cost and operational complexity.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Another option for IDS placement is within the actual network.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] These will reveal attacks or suspicious activity within the network.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Ignoring the security within a network can cause many problems, it will either allow users to bring about security risks or allow an attacker who has already broken into the network to roam around freely.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Intense intranet security makes it difficult for even those hackers within the network to maneuver around and escalate their privileges.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The earliest preliminary IDS concept was delineated in 1980 by James Anderson at the National Security Agency and consisted of a set of tools intended to help administrators review audit trails.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] User access logs, file access logs, and system event logs are examples of audit trails.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Fred Cohen noted in 1987 that it is impossible to detect an intrusion in every case, and that the resources needed to detect intrusions grow with the amount of usage.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Neumann, published a model of an IDS in 1986 that formed the basis for many systems today.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Her model used statistics for anomaly detection, and resulted in an early IDS at SRI International named the Intrusion Detection Expert System (IDES), which ran on Sun workstations and could consider both user and network level data.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] IDES had a dual approach with a rule-based Expert System to detect known types of intrusions plus a statistical anomaly detection component based on profiles of users, host systems, and target systems.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The author of "IDES: An Intelligent System for Detecting Intruders", Teresa F.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Lunt, proposed adding an artificial neural network as a third component.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] She said all three components could then report to a resolver.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] SRI followed IDES in 1993 with the Next-generation Intrusion Detection Expert System (NIDES).
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The Multics intrusion detection and alerting system (MIDAS), an expert system using P-BEST and Lisp, was developed in 1988 based on the work of Denning and Neumann.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Haystack was also developed in that year using statistics to reduce audit trails.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] In 1986 the National Security Agency started an IDS research transfer program under Rebecca Bace.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Bace later published the seminal text on the subject, *Intrusion Detection*, in 2000.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Wisdom & Sense (W&S) was a statistics-based anomaly detector developed in 1989 at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] W&S created rules based on statistical analysis, and then used those rules for anomaly detection.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] In 1990, the Time-based Inductive Machine (TIM) did anomaly detection using inductive learning of sequential user patterns in Common Lisp on a VAX 3500 computer.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Security Monitor (NSM) performed masking on access matrices for anomaly detection on a Sun-3/50 workstation.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The Information Security Officer's Assistant (ISOA) was a 1990 prototype that considered a variety of strategies including statistics, a profile checker, and an expert system.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] ComputerWatch at AT&T Bell Labs used statistics and rules for audit data reduction and intrusion detection.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Then, in 1991, researchers at the University of California, Davis created a prototype Distributed Intrusion Detection System (DIDS), which was also an expert system.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Anomaly Detection and Intrusion Reporter (NADIR), also in 1991, was a prototype IDS developed at the Los Alamos National Laboratory's Integrated Computing Network (ICN), and was heavily influenced by the work of Denning and Lunt.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] NADIR used a statistics-based anomaly detector and an expert system.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced Bro in 1998, which used its own rule language for packet analysis from libpcap data.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Network Flight Recorder (NFR) in 1999 also used libpcap.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] APE was developed as a packet sniffer, also using libpcap, in November, 1998, and was renamed Snort one month later.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Snort has since become the world's largest used IDS/IPS system with over 300,000 active users.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] It can monitor both local systems, and remote capture points using the TZSP protocol.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The Audit Data Analysis and Mining (ADAM) IDS in 2001 used tcpdump to build profiles of rules for classifications.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] In 2003, Yongguang Zhang and Wenke Lee argue for the importance of IDS in networks with mobile nodes.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] In 2015, Viegas and his colleagues proposed an anomaly-based intrusion detection engine, aiming System-on-Chip (SoC) for applications in Internet of Things (IoT), for instance.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The proposal applies machine learning for anomaly detection, providing energy-efficiency to a Decision Tree, Naive-Bayes, and k-Nearest Neighbors classifiers implementation in an Atom CPU and its hardware-friendly implementation in a FPGA.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] In the literature, this was the first work that implement each classifier equivalently in software and hardware and measures its energy consumption on both.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Additionally, it was the first time that was measured the energy consumption for extracting each features used to make the network packet classification, implemented in software and hardware.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] Several regulatory frameworks require or recommend intrusion detection capabilities as part of information security compliance.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] In the United States, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule requires covered entities to implement procedures for monitoring log-in attempts and reporting discrepancies as part of their information system activity review.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The December 2024 Notice of proposed rulemaking (NPRM) to overhaul the HIPAA Security Rule would explicitly mandate deployment of intrusion detection and intrusion prevention systems, along with continuous monitoring of all information systems containing electronic protected health information.
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires the use of intrusion detection or intrusion prevention techniques to detect or prevent intrusions into networks handling cardholder data (Requirement 11.5).
[src:falco-runtime/intrusion-detection-system] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP 800-53 includes the SI-4 (Information System Monitoring) control family, which specifies intrusion detection as a core capability for federal information systems.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] On Unix-like operating systems, this feature can be seen as an advanced implementation of the standard chroot mechanism, which changes the apparent root folder for the current running process and its children.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] In addition to isolation mechanisms, the kernel often provides resource-management features to limit the impact of one container's activities on other containers.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Linux containers are all based on the virtualization, isolation, and resource management mechanisms provided by the Linux kernel, notably Linux namespaces and cgroups.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Although the word *container* most commonly refers to OS-level virtualization, it is sometimes used to refer to fuller virtual machines operating in varying degrees of concert with the host OS, such as Microsoft's Hyper-V containers.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] For an overview of virtualization since 1960, see Timeline of virtualization technologies.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] On ordinary operating systems for personal computers, a computer program can see (even though it might not be able to access) all the system's resources.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may allow or deny access to such resources based on which program requests them and the user account in the context in which it runs.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may also hide those resources, so that when the computer program enumerates them, they do not appear in the enumeration results.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Nevertheless, from a programming point of view, the computer program has interacted with those resources and the operating system has managed an act of interaction.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] With operating-system-virtualization, or containerization, it is possible to run programs within containers, to which only parts of these resources are allocated.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] A program expecting to see the whole computer, once run inside a container, can only see the allocated resources and believes them to be all that is available.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Several containers can be created on each operating system, to each of which a subset of the computer's resources is allocated.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Each container may contain any number of computer programs.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] These programs may run concurrently or separately, and may even interact with one another.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Containerization has similarities to application virtualization: In the latter, only one computer program is placed in an isolated container and the isolation applies to file system only.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is commonly used in virtual hosting environments, where it is useful for securely allocating finite hardware resources among a large number of mutually-distrusting users.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] System administrators may also use it for consolidating server hardware by moving services on separate hosts into containers on the one server.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization can also be used to run software created for a certain Linux distribution on another distribution, an example is Distrobox.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Other typical scenarios include separating several programs to separate containers for improved security, hardware independence, and added resource management features.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] The improved security provided by the use of a chroot mechanism, however, is not perfect.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system-level virtualization implementations capable of live migration can also be used for dynamic load balancing of containers between nodes in a cluster.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] This form of virtualization also does not require hardware support for efficient performance.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is not as flexible as other virtualization approaches since it cannot host a guest operating system different from the host one, or a different guest kernel.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] For example, with Linux, different distributions are fine, but other operating systems such as Windows cannot be hosted.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Operating systems using variable input systematics are subject to limitations within the virtualized architecture.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Adaptation methods including cloud-server relay analytics maintain the OS-level virtual environment within these applications.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Solaris partially overcomes the limitation described above with its branded zones feature, which provides the ability to run an environment within a container that emulates an older Solaris 8 or 9 version in a Solaris 10 host.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] However, in 2010 Linux branded zones were removed from Solaris; in 2014 they were reintroduced in Illumos, which is the open source Solaris fork, supporting 32-bit Linux kernels.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Some implementations provide file-level copy-on-write (CoW) mechanisms.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] (Most commonly, a standard file system is shared between partitions, and those partitions that change the files automatically create their own copies.) This is easier to back up, more space-efficient and simpler to cache than the block-level copy-on-write schemes common on whole-system virtualizers.
[src:falco-runtime/os-level-virtualization] Whole-system virtualizers, however, can work with non-native file systems and create and roll back snapshots of the entire system state.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] In computing, a **system call** (**syscall**) is the programmatic way in which a computer program requests a service from the operating system on which it is executed.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] This may include hardware-related services (for example, accessing a hard disk drive or accessing the device's camera), creation and execution of new processes, and communication with integral kernel services such as process scheduling.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] System calls provide an essential interface between a process and the operating system.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] In most systems, system calls can only be made from userspace processes, while in some systems, OS/360 and successors for example, privileged system code also issues system calls.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] For embedded systems, system calls typically do not change the privilege mode of the CPU.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] The architecture of most modern processors, with the exception of some embedded systems, involves a security model.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] However, many applications need access to these components, so system calls are made available by the operating system to provide well-defined, safe implementations for such operations.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] The operating system executes at the highest level of privilege, and allows applications to request services via system calls, which are often initiated via interrupts.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] An interrupt automatically puts the CPU into some elevated privilege level and then passes control to the kernel, which determines whether the calling program should be granted the requested service.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] If the service is granted, the kernel executes a specific set of instructions over which the calling program has no direct control, returns the privilege level to that of the calling program, and then returns control to the calling program.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] Generally, systems provide a library or API that sits between normal programs and the operating system.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] On Unix-like systems, that API is usually part of an implementation of the C library (libc), such as glibc, that provides wrapper functions for the system calls, often named the same as the system calls they invoke.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] On Windows NT, that API is part of the Native API, in the ntdll.dll library; this is an undocumented API used by implementations of the regular Windows API and directly used by some system programs on Windows.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] The library's wrapper functions expose an ordinary function calling convention (a subroutine call on the assembly level) for using the system call, as well as making the system call more modular.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] Here, the primary function of the wrapper is to place all the arguments to be passed to the system call in the appropriate processor registers (and maybe on the call stack as well), and also setting a unique system call number for the kernel to call.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] In this way the library, which exists between the OS and the application, increases portability.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] The call to the library function itself does not cause a switch to kernel mode and is usually a normal subroutine call (using, for example, a "CALL" assembly instruction in some Instruction set architectures (ISAs)).
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] The actual system call does transfer control to the kernel (and is more implementation-dependent and platform-dependent than the library call abstracting it).
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] For example, in Unix-like systems, `fork` and `execve` are C library functions that in turn execute instructions that invoke the `fork` and `exec` system calls.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] On exokernel based systems, the library is especially important as an intermediary.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] On exokernels, libraries shield user applications from the very low level kernel API, and provide abstractions and resource management.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] IBM's OS/360, DOS/360 and TSS/360 implement most system calls through a library of assembly language macros, although there are a few services with a call linkage.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] This reflects their origin at a time when programming in assembly language was more common than high-level language usage.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] IBM system calls were therefore not directly executable by high-level language programs, but required a callable assembly language wrapper subroutine.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] Since then, IBM has added many services that can be called from high level languages in, e.g., z/OS and z/VSE.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] In more recent release of MVS/SP and in all later MVS versions, some system call macros generate Program Call (PC).
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] On Unix, Unix-like and other POSIX-compliant operating systems, popular system calls are `open`, `read`, `write`, `close`, `wait`, `exec`, `fork`, `exit`, and `kill`.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] Many modern operating systems have hundreds of system calls.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] For example, Linux and OpenBSD each have over 300 different calls, NetBSD has close to 500, FreeBSD has over 500, Windows has close to 2000, divided between win32k (graphical) and ntdll (core) system calls while Plan 9 has 54.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] Tools such as strace, ftrace and truss allow a process to execute from start and report all system calls the process invokes, or can attach to an already running process and intercept any system call made by the said process if the operation does not violate the permissions of the user.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] This special ability of the program is usually also implemented with system calls such as ptrace or system calls on files in procfs.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] Implementing system calls requires a transfer of control from user space to kernel space, which involves some sort of architecture-specific feature.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] A typical way to implement this is to use a software interrupt or trap.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] Interrupts transfer control to the operating system kernel, so software simply needs to set up some register with the system call number needed, and execute the software interrupt.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] This is the only technique provided for many RISC processors, but CISC architectures such as x86 support additional techniques.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] For example, the x86 instruction set contains the instructions `SYSCALL`/`SYSRET` and `SYSENTER`/`SYSEXIT` (these two mechanisms were independently created by AMD and Intel, respectively, but in essence they do the same thing).
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] These are "fast" control transfer instructions that are designed to quickly transfer control to the kernel for a system call without the overhead of an interrupt.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] Linux 2.5 began using this on the x86, where available; formerly it used the `INT` instruction, where the system call number was placed in the `EAX` register before interrupt 0x80 was executed.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] An older mechanism is the call gate; originally used in Multics and later, for example, see call gate on the Intel x86.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] It allows a program to call a kernel function directly using a safe control transfer mechanism, which the operating system sets up in advance.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] For IA-64 architecture, `EPC` (Enter Privileged Code) instruction is used.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] The first eight system call arguments are passed in registers, and the rest are passed on the stack.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] In the IBM System/360 mainframe family, and its successors, a Supervisor Call instruction (SVC), with the number in the instruction rather than in a register, implements a system call for legacy facilities in most of IBM's own operating systems, and for all system calls in Linux.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] In later versions of MVS, IBM uses the Program Call (PC) instruction for many newer facilities.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] In particular, PC is used when the caller might be in Service Request Block (SRB) mode.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] The PDP-11 minicomputer used the EMT, TRAP and IOT instructions, which, similar to the IBM System/360 SVC and x86 INT, put the code in the instruction; they generate interrupts to specific addresses, transferring control to the operating system.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] The VAX 32-bit successor to the PDP-11 series used the CHMK, CHME, and CHMS instructions to make system calls to privileged code at various levels; the code is an argument to the instruction.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] Within the RISC-V privileged architecture, the instruction `ECALL` (after *environment call*) is designed to enter a more privileged level and therefore this instruction performs the functionalities related to system calls.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] `ECALL` events are then handled in a similar fashion to other types of synchronous traps, including the same return mechanism.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] In the related Linux implementations, the system call number is placed into the `a7` (`x17`) register before `ECALL` is executed, function arguments are listed in accordance to the RISC-V ABI (`a0`, `a1`, ...) while the return value is put in `a0`.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] System calls in most Unix-like systems are processed in kernel mode, which is accomplished by changing the processor execution mode to a more privileged one, but no *process* context switch is necessary – although a *privilege* context switch does occur.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] The hardware sees the world in terms of the execution mode according to the processor status register, and processes are an abstraction provided by the operating system.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] A system call does not generally require a context switch to another process; instead, it is processed in the context of whichever process invoked it.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] In a multithreaded process, system calls can be made from multiple threads.
[src:falco-runtime/system-call] The handling of such calls is dependent on the design of the specific operating system kernel and the application runtime environment.
